n sundered by modern disciplinary boundaries, Love at a Crux unearths the interconnections between New Persian and comparable traditions in ancient and medieval Greek, Arabic, Georgian, Old French, and Middle High German, offering scholars in classics, medieval studies, Middle Eastern literatures, and premodern world literature a case study in literary history as connected history.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLove in literature. 0aPersian literaturey747-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aRomances, PersianxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArabic.  aFrench.  aGreek.  aIran.  aMiddle Eastern literature.  aPersian literature.  aPersian poetry.  aVis and Ramin.  aclassics.  acomparative literature.  ahistory of romantic literature.  alove stories.  amedieval.  anovel.  aromance.2 aUniversity of Toronto Librariesefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487553128zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487553128zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487553128/original  a978-3-11-079736-7 University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA